This Bank Management System is a simple Python application that simulates some of the basic operations performed in a real bank. It uses the Pandas library to manage customer data and stores all records in a CSV file called *customers.csv*. Instead of relying on a database management system, the program uses this CSV file as a storage medium, making it easier for beginners to understand how data can be stored and retrieved. The system allows users to add new customers, deposit money, withdraw money, and view customer records through a menu-driven interface.

When the program starts, it first prepares the environment by importing the Pandas library and specifying the CSV file where customer information will be stored. The customer data consists of three main fields: Customer ID, Customer Name, and Account Balance. Whenever the program needs to access customer information, it reads the data from the CSV file and loads it into a Pandas DataFrame, which functions like a table. If the file does not already exist, the program automatically creates a new empty file with the required columns. This ensures that the application can run smoothly even when it is being used for the first time.

A key feature of the program is its ability to save data permanently. Every time a customer is added or an account balance is updated, the latest information is written back to the CSV file. This means that all changes remain stored even after the program is closed. As a result, the CSV file acts as a simple database that keeps track of customer records over time.

The customer registration feature allows users to create new bank accounts. When this option is selected, the program asks the user to enter a customer ID, customer name, and an initial account balance. Once the information is provided, a new customer record is created and added to the existing list of customers. The updated records are then saved, ensuring that the new customer becomes part of the system. This process closely resembles the account creation procedure followed in actual banking environments.

The deposit functionality enables users to add money to an existing account. The program first asks for the customer ID and the amount to be deposited. Before updating the balance, it checks whether the customer exists in the system. If the customer is found, the specified amount is added to the current balance and the updated information is saved. If the customer ID does not exist, an appropriate message is displayed. This validation helps maintain the accuracy of the records and prevents transactions from being performed on invalid accounts.

Similarly, the withdrawal feature allows users to remove money from an account. After the customer ID and withdrawal amount are entered, the program verifies that the customer exists and retrieves the current account balance. It then checks whether there are sufficient funds available to complete the transaction. If enough money is available, the withdrawal amount is deducted and the updated balance is saved. Otherwise, the program informs the user that the account does not have sufficient funds. This safeguard prevents negative balances and reflects the basic rules followed by real banking systems.

The program also includes a feature to display customer records. When selected, it retrieves all stored customer information and presents it in a clear tabular format. If no customer data is available, the user is informed accordingly. This functionality provides a quick and convenient way to view all accounts and their current balances.

To make the application user-friendly, all operations are controlled through a menu that is displayed repeatedly until the user decides to exit. The menu allows users to choose from different banking operations, and the program performs the corresponding task based on the selected option. After each operation is completed, the menu appears again, allowing the user to continue working without restarting the program. The application only terminates when the user explicitly chooses the exit option.

Overall, this project is a practical example of how Python can be used to build a simple data management system. It combines important programming concepts such as functions, loops, conditional statements, exception handling, file handling, and data manipulation with Pandas. Although the application is relatively small, it demonstrates how real-world systems manage, update, and store information. For beginners, it serves as an excellent project because it provides hands-on experience with both programming fundamentals and basic software design principles while solving a realistic problem.
